2 company, or affiliate of those entities or business associations which exists to
3 make a profit and which has ten or more ful l - time employees and has a value o f
4 one hundred thousand dollars or more. The term does not include a sole
5 proprietorship.
6 c. "Governmental entity" means a state agency or political subdivision of this state.
7 d. "Ordinary business purpose" means any motive directly related to:
8 (1) Promoting the financial success or stability of the company;
9 (2) Mitigating risk to the company;
10 (3) Complying with legal or regulatory requirements; or
11 (4) Limiting liability of the company.
12 2. This section applies to a contract between a governmental entity and a company
13 which is to be paid wholly or in part from public funds.
14 3. Except as provided in subsection 4, a governmental entity may not enter a contract
15 with a company for goods or services unless the contract contains a written verification
16 the company does not engage in a boycott as described in subsection 1 and is no t
17 included on a list of financial institutions not eligible to receive investments of state
18 funds by the state investment board.
19 4. Subsection 3 does not apply to a contract if the governmental entity determines and
20 documents the goods or services are not otherwise available on commercially
21 reasonable terms or if subsection 3 is inconsistent with the governmental entity's
22 constitutional or statutory duties.
23 SECTION 2. APPLICATION. This Act applies to a contract entered after the effective date
24 of this Act. A contract entered before the effective date of this Act which violates this Act may not
25 be renewed unless the governmental entity obtains the written verification described in this Act.
